Transportation at Church events

Introduction

This data explores how members of my church community traveled to events, church camp and then our church Sunday celebration. We examine how many people were in each car, whether the car was shared or not, and the reasons people took multiple cars.

How full were the cars?

Bar chart showing occupancy rates by date

This plot shows how full the cars were on different dates. The bar height shows how many cars had a certain occupancy rate (how many people per seat).

The goal here is to assess carpooling efficiency. We can see how usage varied between the two events (each date is colored differently). Lower occupancy rates may indicate cars with few passengers.

Does car sharing depend on how full the car is?

Line chart comparing car occupancy and whether it was the only car

This chart compares how many people were in each car and whether that car was the only one used by that group.

You can see trends based on how full the car was: whether larger groups tended to carpool or still used multiple cars. Each line represents “Yes” (this was their only car) or “No” (they brought other cars too).

Why did some groups take more than one car?

Line chart showing reasons for multiple cars and occupancy

This plot looks only at the people who said this was not their only car. It explores why they took multiple cars — such as “Different arrival times” or “Needed space for prams.”

Each line is a different reason, and the x-axis shows how many people were in each car. It gives us a more nuanced picture of why multiple cars were necessary — even when the car wasn’t full.
